tr.td: Primary Care Outpatient Visit for Diabetes Management

td.content: Glynda Sugarman, a 56-year-old female with a history of obesity, hypertension, hyperlipidemia, and type 2 diabetes mellitus (DM2), presents for follow-up. Her DM2 is moderately controlled with recent blood glucose levels between 150-200 mg/dL. She reports occasional dietary non-compliance and has been inconsistent with her exercise regimen. Two weeks ago, she started Ozempic (semaglutide) 0.25 mg SC weekly, which has helped reduce her appetite. She reports mild nausea but no other significant side effects. Her last HbA1c was 6.8% (07/2023) and microalbumin/creatinine ratio was 15 mg/g (07/2023). She has been counseled on diabetes management, lifestyle modifications, and medication adherence. The plan includes continuation of Metformin 1000 mg PO BID and Ozempic with consideration for titration, and scheduling of tests including HbA1c, lipid profile, and renal function tests. A comprehensive foot exam was performed, and she was referred for a dilated eye exam.

tr.td: Ophthalmology Exam for Diabetic Retinopathy Screening

td.content: 56-year-old female with a history of moderately controlled type 2 diabetes mellitus (diagnosed 10 years ago), obesity, and hypertension was referred for a routine diabetic retinopathy screening. Her current medications include Metformin 1000 mg PO BID, Ozempic 0.25 mg SC weekly, Lisinopril 20 mg PO daily, and Atorvastatin 40 mg PO daily. She reports no recent vision changes. Examination revealed normal visual acuity (20/25 bilaterally) and normal intraocular pressure (16 mmHg in the right eye and 15 mmHg in the left eye). Dilated fundus exam showed no evidence of diabetic retinopathy, but mild hypertensive changes were noted in the retinal vessels. The optic nerves were healthy with a cup-to-disc ratio of 0.3 bilaterally, and there was no macular edema or exudates. Patient was advised to maintain good blood pressure control and to return for an annual dilated eye exam or sooner if vision changes occur.

tr.td: Cesarean Section Due to Breech Presentation

td.content: Glynda Sugarman, a 56-year-old female, underwent a cesarean section on 05/01/2001 at full term due to breech presentation. The patient was brought to the operating room, and a Pfannenstiel incision was made. The uterus was opened in a transverse fashion, and the breech presentation was confirmed. The infant's feet were delivered first, followed by the rest of the body. Apgar scores were 9 at 1 minute and 10 at 5 minutes. The uterus was closed in two layers, and hemostasis was confirmed. The patient tolerated the procedure well with minimal estimated blood loss. No complications were noted during or after the surgery, and she was transferred to the postpartum unit in stable condition. Postoperative recovery was uneventful.
